Commentary.Commentary: The Windies have been out on the field for almost two days, they would be mentally and physically drained and that is what England would want. The visitors will now face a tricky period where they have around 15 overs to bat out till Stumps. The home side will be looking for a couple of wickets whereas, the visitors will hope they can enter Day 3 unscathed. Do join us for the final phase of play of Day 2.

The Windies bowlers gave it their all, they bowled with discipline and with a lot of heart. A couple of their bowlers faced injury issues which did not help their cause. To add to that, the wicket also wasn't assisting the pacers a lot but it did provide purchase to their only spinner who is also the pick of the bowlers, Chase. He finishes with a fifer. Roach had two to his name. Joseph and Holder took one each whereas, Gabriel failed to pick even one.

Finally, the England innings comes to an end! They have declared at 469/9. The hosts though would have loved to reach the 500-run mark but the acceleration did not quite go as they planned. They kept losing wickets at regular intervals but 469 is still a big score and it is basically because of the contributions of the two batters, Sibley who scored his second ton and Stokes who scored his 10th Test ton. The two added over 250, they took their own time and now have England in a very promising position. Nobody except for the two contributed a lot. Buttler did get off to a start. Bess played a decent cameo towards the end but it was Stokes and Sibley's partnership which was the highlight.

Man of the moment, Ben Stokes leads the field as the players head out for Tea. Another session that belonged to England. The hosts are completely in command of this game and are cruising at this stage. The hosts have piled on runs and unlike the previous sessions Ben Stokes has changed gears as the hosts have scored 114 runs in this session. West Indies did manage to get 2 wickets, that of Sibley and Pope but the English all-rounder is looking comfortable and going about his business like his usual aggressive self. He is unbeaten on 172 and partnered by Jos Buttler. It will be interesting to see what Root and co decide to do in the final session as rain is expected to spoil Day 3. The tourists, on the other hand, would look to strike early in the final session and if asked to bat today would like to start with some momentum. What do we have in store in the final session? Join us at 1615 local (1515 GMT) to find out.

Hello and welcome to Day 2 of the 2nd Test between England and West Indies. It was a slow and steady Day 1 but it were the hosts who had the upper hand. Sibley has been patient and will look to continue to keep his calm and composure and do the same. Stokes too played a very disciplined innings and showed his maturity. The pair have added 126 runs and would look to build on it. West Indies, on the other hand, will not be disheartened as they haven't leaked a lot of runs and can begin the day with the new ball. The tourists would look to put on a better show with the second new ball and look to strike early and end this stand. What do we have in store on Day 2?
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

The day though began brilliantly for the visitors, they won the toss, elected to bowl under overcast conditions, got two early wickets, dismissed Root but after that, their bowlers have had no answers to the stubbornness of Stokes and Sibley. To add to that, their star from the first Test, Gabriel, did not seem to be at his best and was struggling with fitness. Despite all of that though, the Windies would know a couple of quick wickets on Day 2 and they are right back in this. However, another good partnership will see them fall well behind in the game. An important first session awaits. Do join us at 1100 local (1000 GMT). Till then, take care and goodbye!

A good session of Test cricket. England were straightaway on the back foot as they lost Crawley in the first ball of the session but Root and Sibley solidified the innings with a -run stand before the skipper departed. Sibley though has been going along nicely and has had no problem in leaving and defending deliveries. Stokes too has been cautious in his approach and the pair have added 31 so far. West Indies will be happy with their effort as they managed  to pick two wickets and have kept the run check at bay. A shared session is what one can say and this Test match has been nicely poised on the first day so far. It started to go dark towards the end of the session but let's hope we get full final session without any interruption. Who will finish Day 1 on the front foot? Join us at 1645 local (1545 GMT) for the final session to find out.

We are back for the second session on Day 1. Crawley joins Sibley out in the middle. Chase to finish off the over. The natural lights are getting better, that's a good news we wanted to hear. Here we go...
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

A good little session of Test cricket! The English started off well, their batters were solid to begin with and managed to get their partnership off to a start but a master move by Holder to bring on Chase saw them get a wicket they would have desperately wanted. The Windies would want to continue taking wickets after the break whereas England would hope they could build partnerships. Let's hope we have a long good session of Test cricket.

Strays down the line this time! Good length ball down the leg side, Burns looks to flick but fails to get any bat on it.
Very full delivery outside off, swinging away from the batsman, Burns has no problems in leaving the ball alone.
Roach starts with an outswinging full ball outside off, Burns watches the first ball of the day and leaves the ball alone.

All set for the match to begin! 83 overs will be bowled in the day with Lunch being taken at 1330 Local and the play can go on till 1900 Local. The West Indies' players make their way out to the middle, followed by Rory Burns and Dom Sibley. Kemar Roach will start the proceedings with the ball. The players are taking a knee to show support for the Black Lives Matter movement.

Joe Root, the England skipper, says that they did not want what happened with Jofra Archer in the morning. Adds that they did not think about taking Anderson and Wood after the Jofra incident because they are coming back after injuries and they want to keep a check on them. Further says that they are playing Broad, Curran, Woakes and Bess. Goes on to say that they need to improve on the first innings and he is happy that the players showed character. States that they are positive for this game and they are looking forward to it. Adds that it is a good wicket to bat on and they will look to give in good performances.

West Indies skipper, Jason Holder, says they want to make use of the overhead conditions hence the decision. Informs they are unchanged from their last game. On the bowlers, he says they have held up quite well and he expects them to continue to do it. Tells the most important thing is to learn and keep growing. Says the victory has made a lot of people back home smile and they want that to continue.

West Indies (Unchanged Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite, John Campbell, Shai Hope, Shamarh Brooks, Roston Chase, Jermaine Blackwood, Shane Dowrich (WK), Jason Holder (C), Alzarri Joseph, Kemar Roach, Shannon Gabriel.

England (Playing XI) - Rory Burns, Dom Sibley, Zak Crawley, Joe Root (C) (In place of Joe Denly), Ben Stokes, Ollie Pope, Jos Buttler (WK), Chris Woakes (In place of Jofra Archer), Sam Curran (In place of Mark Wood), Dom Bess, Stuart Broad (In place of James Anderson).
Toss - Time for the Toss. Up goes the coin and it lands in favour of Jason Holder. They have elected to bowl first.

Just like the first Test, the start of the second Test was also delayed due to rain. We are all set to get underway now as the rain has stopped.  After being humbled in the first Test by the visitors, the hosts received a boost in the form of Joe Root, who has returned to the squad and they will expect that he leads his team to a victory and level the series. But, they have been dealt a big blow with Jofra Archer being ruled out of the Test as he breached the bio-secure protocols. He will be spending 5 days in quarantine and will undergo 2 Covid-19 tests before he can rejoin the squad. This is a big blow as he was England's best bowler in the first Test. Who will replace him? That question will be an interesting one to keep an eye on.  They need their batting to pull their socks up and stick it out in the middle. West Indies, on the other hand, have plenty to be pleased about. They won the first match comfortably and will be looking to repeat the performance and win the series with one game to spare. Hello and welcome to the second Test between England and West Indies.

So, a few overs left for England to face. Will they go for quick runs in this final phase of the play? Will they change the batting line-up? Maybe they send Buttler as an opener and play some T20 cricket. We will soon find out what happens in a bit when the English innings start. Hang on with us.

England's bowling, not bad at all but they had their limitations after Day 3 was washed out completely. They needed more wickets earlier in the day but that did not come as early as they wanted. When they took the second new ball, Broad took quick wickets and it looked like they might bundle West Indies before the follow-on target. But that didn't happen. Broad and Woakes finished with a 3-fer while Curran got 2.

Joseph, the nightwatchman fell early but Brathwaite along with Hope and then with Brooks steadied the ship and added important runs with both the batters getting to their half tons. Chase too played a very good knock of 51 and helped the team avoid the follow-on.

Right! A decent batting performance from West Indies to avoid the follow-on. They wouldn't be too happy though as they were in a pretty strong position at Tea but lost wickets in clusters in this session. But they have managed to get past the follow-on challenge and have forced England to bat again.

OUT! Bowled! The slower ball does the trick and West Indies are bowled out now. Woakes smartly takes the pace off this one and bowls it on a length, Gabriel looks to defend but gets deceived by the lack of pace. The ball also moves away a bit, squaring up Gabriel and hitting the off pole. West Indies bowled out for 287! Trail by 182.
Bouncer! Gabriel sits under it.

Ouch that must have hurt. We all know it did. Good length ball around leg, Gabriel looks to defend but misses and gets hit flush on the box. Ouch! Roach is having a laugh but bet Gabriel is not enjoying a bit.
Outside off, Shannon looks to defend but misses.
Full around off, Gabriel blocks it.

Another very good ball from Woakes and he has his second of the innings. Full and quick around off, Chase looks to defend but misses due to the pace and the movement. A couple for Chase and he gets to his half ton. A full ball on the pads, he flicks it towards deep square leg.

Good length delivery around off, Chase pushes it towards point.
Another leave as Woakes bowls this length ball outside off.

Good length ball on middle, Roach works it towards the leg side and calls for a run but Chase says no.
In the air but just short. Fuller on middle, Chase looks to loft it over mid on but does not get the elevation. The ball falls on Woakes at mid on. He dives but still can't reach.

On the leg side, Chase flicks it to the on side.

On the pads, Chase glances it towards mid-wicket.
FOUR! Just one more hit  needed now to avoid the follow on. Curran bowls it on middle and leg, looking for a LBW but Chase is quick to flick it through mid-wicket for a boundary.

We are back for the final segment on Day 4. The English players have stepped on the field and Shamarh Brooks and Roston Chase follow them. England need wickets and in clusters if they are to force a result in this Test. Skipper Joe Root gives them the final advice in a huddle. Stuart Broad to begin the session with the ball for England. Here we go...
... Day 4, Session 3 ...

A good session for West Indies as they lost two wickets but have edged closer to avoid the follow-on which is their first target. The post Lunch session did not begin the way they would have wanted as they lost Hope early but Brooks joined Brathwaite in the fight and the pair added 76 before the opener was dismissed against the run of play for 75. Brooks though has continued his battle and is looking impressive on 60. England needed more than the 2 wickets but have found it difficult. The bowlers have put in a lot of effort though but to little success. The new ball is not far away and the hosts would like to make the most of it in the final session and try to bowl the tourists out. A very decisive session awaits us as we find out which way this Test is headed. Join us for the last session of Day 4 to find out.
Yes, he has negotiated as he works this shortish ball towards mid-wicket for a single. TEA ON DAY 4!

Nasser Hussain rings the bell and we are all set for the action to begin! Chris Woakes has the ball in hand and he will be bowling to Kraigg Brathwaite. Here we go...

2 days to go, almost 200 overs to be bowled, 19 wickets is what England need to level the series, do they have the bowlers to do so? They will have to give it their all or winning the series becomes impossible. For the Windies, a win looks highly unlikely, a win will be nothing less than a miracle for them, however, a draw is something they won't mind but for that, they will have to bat well too. Their first goal will be to avoid the follow-on and then get as close as possible to the hosts' total. The first session can indicate to which way this game is going. The weather is all clear here in Manchester and we can't wait for the game to begin. Welcome to the coverage of Day 4. Stay tuned....

Hello and welcome to the coverage of Day 3 of the second Test between England and West Indies. First things first, let's talk about the weather, it is raining at the moment. We did mention the forecast is not good on Day 3 and the rain gods have had no mercy. The covers are on and an on-time start looks improbable.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

England's day! They are in firm control of this game. They batted most of the day, ensured that the Windies toiled for more than two sessions as they put a mammoth score and then have also managed to send one of the openers packing. They would have obviously loved another, they could have got another had they reviewed on the second last ball of the day but they will be happy with their overall work. More of the same is what Root will be hoping for on Day 3. West Indies, on the other hand, would hope their batters to deliver, partnerships is what they need and they will be eager to get close to if not surpass the English total. However, what the visitors won't mind too is some rain. The forecast is not good for Day 3, England though would hope the rain gods have mercy on them and stay away. Do join us for all the action at 1100 local (1000 GMT).
On a good length on off, Alzarri keeps it out. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 2!

Howzattttt? The umpire shakes his head! Curran really likes it. He has a word with his skipper about a review but Root does not. Coming to the ball. It is a full one, excellent from Curran follows the short one with a really full one which tails back in from outside off. Joseph looks to jam it out but there are two noises. Curran appeals feeling it brushed the pad first but the umpire shakes his head. England do not review but... replays just show that it brushed the pad first. Maybe if it had been a top order player, they would have probably gone for it but since it was Joseph, they might have decided against. All Curran can do now is smile.
FOUR! Curran bowls a bouncer, Joseph looks to pull but it goes off the top edge. It goes over the keeper towards fine leg for a boundary.
Good length delivery on off, Joseph blocks it off the front foot.
On a good length on off, Joseph defends it out.
On a length on middle, Brathwaite plays it towards mid on and takes a quick single.
Outside off, Alzarri offers no shot to this one.
Loopy delivery on off, Joseph punches it to point.
Full delivery on off, Joseph lofts it over covers. The fielder chases it and does well to stop it. The batsmen get two runs.
Floated delivery on off, Joseph defends it out.
Flighted delivery on middle, Joseph blocks it well.
Tossed up delivery on off, Joseph drives it back towards the bowler.
On a length on middle, Brathwaite flicks it towards the leg side.
Good length delivery on off, Kraigg keeps it out.
On a good length on off, Brathwaite blocks it off the back foot.
Length delivery on leg, Joseph flicks it towards fine leg for a single.
Good length delivery outside off, Joseph shoulders arms to this one.
On a length on middle, Joseph flicks it through mid-wicket. The batsmen get two runs.
On off, Joseph drives it through covers. The fielder chases it and does well to stop it. The batsmen get three runs.
Flighted delivery on off, Joseph looks to defend but gets an outside edge. It goes towards third man. The batsmen get two runs.
On middle, Brathwaite flicks it through square leg for a run.
Loopy delivery on off, Brathwaite drives it towards mid off.
Floated delivery on middle, Brathwaite drives it towards mid on.
Tossed up delivery on off, Brathwaite plays it towards mid off.
Outside off, left alone. End of a successful over by Curran.
Fuller and on middle, driven to mid off.
Nightwatchman Alzarri Joseph is the new batsman in.

OUT! THREE REDS! Campbell is a goner! An excellent bowling change from Root! Curran has this habit of picking up a wicket when his team needs it. Just 4 balls into his first over and he gets rid of one opener. Excellent review too! Curran bowls it full and around off, it shapes in a touch. He got this one to come in after taking the last two away. Campbell looks to drive but there are two noises. It has hit the pad for sure but is it bat-pad or pad and pad? England appeal and the umpire feels its the former and shakes his head. England review. Replays show it is front pad and back pad. Time for the Hawk Eye and it shows the on-field call has to be overturned. Another low score for Campbell, England would like one more before Stumps.
Review time! An appeal for lbw! John Campbell is the man in question.
On a good length on off, Campbell blocks it off the front foot.
Good length delivery outside off, John leaves it alone.
On a good length on off, Campbell plays it to point.
Good length delivery on off, Brathwaite keeps it out.
On a good length on off, Kraigg defends it off the back foot.
Outside off, Brathwaite shoulders arms to this one.
On a good length and outside off, Brathwaite offers no shot to this one.
Length delivery on middle, Brathwaite flicks it to mid-wicket.
On a length on off, Brathwaite plays it to covers.
Outside off, not played at.
Played to the point region by the batsman.
Back of a length and on off, this is guided to point.
On off, defended nicely.
Outside off, left alone.
Outside off, Campbell leaves it.

How has Campbell got bat on that one? That has not bounced at all. It is on a length and around middle, stays low. Campbell gets his bat down in time and it goes towards fine leg. Broad appeals thinking it is pad first but the umpire shakes his head.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.
FOUR! Sweet is how that can be defined! Fuller and around off, Campbell leans into it and creams it through mid off for a boundary. The Windies batters have started off well here.
Well played! Length and around off, it skids through. Campbell gets his bat down in time and keeps it out.
On a good length and around off, defended nicely.
On middle, Campbell keeps it out nicely.
The batsman tries flicking a ball that is down the leg side.
One more delivery outside off, left alone again.
On the stumps, kept out.
One more ball outside off, Brathwaite shoulders arms to this one.
Outside off again, left alone.
On middle, defended solidly.
FOUR! First real poor ball by Broad and Campbell puts it away. Full and angled into the pads, the batter clips it in style through mid-wicket for a boundary. First of the innings.
Just outside off, Campbell watches it and lets it be.
BEATEN! Broad is so good to the left-handers. Comes from around the wicket, angles it into the batter, he gets it to leave him after pitching. Campbell is beaten as he tries to defend.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
A little too straight. Campbell looks to flick but misses to get hit on the thigh pad.
A single now as this is worked down towards fine leg. Had to put bat to ball there or he would have been an LBW candidate.

Well played in the end! This is shorter and it sticks in the surface. Campbell is committed to the shot a touch early. He though does well to take one hand off the handle and keep it along the ground.
Very full this time and on off, JC pushes it towards cover.
Drags his length back a little, Campbell pushes it through covers and takes an easy two.
This time it is right on off, defended nicely.
Good delivery! This starts around middle and then keeps slanting away with the angle. Campbell is drawn into playing at it but due to the angle away, he gets beaten.
Outside off, nicely left.
A leave to end the over as it is bowled outside off.
Down the leg side, Kraigg looks to flick but misses.
Slightly shorter and width on offer. KB goes back and pushes it through covers for two.
Good movement! Length and around off, it shapes away after pitching. Brathwaite initially looks to poke at it but then bails out.
Outside off, left alone.
Attacks the stumps, kept out.
A little too straight, Campbell looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. A harmless maiden from Woakes.
Lands it outside off, not played at.
Fuller this time but once again not a lot of movement, it is driven towards mid off.
One more length ball outside off, left alone. No movement for Woakes so far.
Length delivery, angling away from off. Left alone.
Good length and on off, kept out.
Chris Woakes to bowl from the other end.
A dot to end as the last ball is pushed towards cover.

A huge shout but it has been turned down. Broad was pretty excited. It is a length delivery outside off, it comes back in a touch.Brathwaite looks to play it with a straight bat but misses to get hit on the pads. An appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Broad, Root and Buttler have a discussion but then don't review. Rightly so as Hawk Eye shows the impact to be outside off.
Well bowled! Lands it around off, gets it to straighten a touch. Brathwaite tries to defend but it goes off the outer half towards cover.
Campbell is off the mark now as he too gets one on the pads, works it towards fine leg for one.
Windies are off the mark! It is on the pads, it is worked towards square leg for one.
Starts off with a delivery outside off, it is left alone.

A couple of early wickets and England will think they have got every chance of bowling West Indies out. They could not do something similar in the first Test though but with the series on the line, they will do all they can. Join for the final inning of this Test in a bit.

West Indies looked a bit nervous with the ball seeing Ben Stokes going all-gun blazing. With Stokes throwing the kitchen sink at everything, they tried bouncers and all they could but couldn't get past Stokes. Now, they have a task in hand. 312 to win the Test match but not sure if they will be thinking on that front. They will look to bat out the sessions and do not allow England an opening.

A perfect morning for England. Exactly the way they wanted. And it is because of just one man, Ben Stokes. He came like a thunder and started striking from the 1st ball. His unbeaten 57-ball 78 has given England a decent cushion of runs and plenty of overs to have a crack at Windies batting with the ball. This game is surely not over as yet.

On the pads, Pope glances it to the on side and gets a single to finish the over. Root comes to the balcony and he has called his players off. England declare at 129/3. West Indies need 312 to win the Test!
WIDE! Holder bowls one down the leg side and the umpire has signalled it as wide. Stokes also steals a run. So one more ball.

Full and wide outside off, Stokes plays it wide of third man and gets a couple. One ball remaining in this over, it could also be the last ball of England's innings as they look ready to take the field.
EDGED AND FOUR! Length ball outside off, Stokes looks to slash it on the off side but gets a thick outside edge which goes wide of the keeper and to the fence.
This time on the pads, Stokes flicks it behind square leg and gets a couple as the fielder there dives to his left and saves a couple. Lead past 300 now, it's 301.
Smart from Holder. He has once again bowled one down the leg side, Stokes looks to flick but misses. The umpire has had a word with Holder for the negative line.
Full toss down the leg side, Stokes looks to flick but misses.
FOUR! Very good shot and the lead now stretches to 299! Length ball outside off, Pope hangs back and cuts it through point for a boundary. England get the boundary they were looking for in the over.
Full and wide outside off, Stokes stretches and plays it to deep point for a single.
Back of a length delivery around off, Pope runs it down to third man and gets a single. Lead is now of 294 runs.
Good fielding! On the pads, Pope plays it fine down the leg side. Hope runs to his right from fine leg and does very well to stop the ball before the ropes. Saves 2 for his side.
On the pads, Stokes flicks it to the on side and gets a single.
Fuller on off and middle, Pope plays the reverse paddle and gives the strike to Stokes.
FOUR! Delicate from Stokes. Short ball around off, Stokes waits for it and then guides it fine towards third man. Roach there gives it a chase but comes second best.
SIX! Stokes has come in T20 mode and that is what his team needs. When he is in such a mood you cannot bowl him in his arc. Holder bowls it full around off, Stokes slams it over long off for a six.
On the pads, Pope tucks it behind square on the leg side and gets a single.
Fuller outside off, Stokes plays it through covers and gets a single.
Outside off, Stokes swings but misses.

NOT OUT! West Indies have lost all their reviews and that has happened very quickly. Full toss on the pads, Pope looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. Holder apeals and in the meantime the batter take a run as the ball goes to the leg side. Jason decides to signal the 'T'. Replay rolls in and Ultra Edge shows a little bit of spike as the ball goes past the bat.

Another huge appeal and West Indies have taken the review again. This time it is against Pope. Looked to be missing the leg but West Indies think otherwise. Let's see what the replays show. Front foot is fine. Any bat involved? Yes, the Ultra Edge detects a spike. Excellent decision from the on-field umpire.
Full and wide outside off, Stokes strokes it wide of third man and gets another brace.
On middle, Stokes plays it wide of long on and gets a couple.
Wide outside off, Stokes throws his bat but misses.
Down the leg side, Stokes looks to flick but misses.

Not Out! Another review has been lost by the West Indies. Pitching around leg, Stokes looks to whip it over on the leg side but misses and gets hit on the pads. Holder decides to take the review. Replay rolls in and it shows that the ball is pitching outside leg again...

Review time! West Indies are desperate to see the back of Ben Stokes. Another review which looks just in desperation. No bat involved. Where is it pitching? Down the leg side. Another review gone for West Indies.
Ollie Pope walks in next.

OUT! RUN OUT! Root sacrifices his wicket for Stokes and the team. Joseph starts with a ball down the leg side. Root looks to flick but misses. Stokes is on his bike to get on strike. Root keeps his head down and runs. Dowrich throws the ball to Holder who comes from mid off and whips the bails off. Root is nowhere in the frame and he has to depart.
Alzarri Joseph is brought into the attack.
Short ball on middle and off, Root pulls it and keeps the strike.
Outside off, Root leaves it alone.
On the pads, Stokes looks to flick but misses and Dowrich fails to gather it cleanly allowing them to steal a bye.
Review time! Looks height but Holder has decided to take the review. Is it to waste some time or dos he genuinely think they have their man?

NOT OUT! Waste of a review. The ball is pitching outside leg so we don't even need to go to check the height. Length delivery on leg, Stokes looks to pull but misses and gets hit on the box. West Indies player put in a mild appeal which is turned down. Holder decides to take the review. Replay rolls in and shows that the ball is pitching outside leg.
On the pads, Root flicks it to fine leg and gets a single.

Low full toss on middle and leg, Stokes whips it to the left of deep mid-wicket and looks for two. The fielder though gets to the ball quickly and Root comes out of his crease. The skipper is sent back but luckily the though at the keeper's end is a poor one and Joe can get back in safely with his dive.
A single and Stokes will keep the strike for the next over as he plays this full toss down to deep square leg.
Good length ball around off, Root looks to pull but ends up getting a bottom edge down to fine leg for a run.
Short and around off, this one is pulled down to deep mid-wicket for a single.

SIX & FIFTY FOR STOKES! He has nailed this time around. 22nd Test half-century for him. He is making sure that the runs come quickly for his team. A fuller ball just outside off, Stokes hammers it over long off for a biggie.
Good length ball outside off, Stokes looks to hammer it again but fails to connect.
Full and around off and middle, Root looks to flick but ends up getting it off the inside edge towards third man. A single taken.
Length ball just around off, Root stays on the back foot and guides it down to third man. They think for the second but the fielder there is quick to the ball so they settle for the single only.
Down the leg side. Root looks to pull but fails to connect. Dowrich does well to gather it on his left.
Very full ball around off, Stokes drills it to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Bumper and a good one too. Stokes does well to evade it.
Full and outside off, Stokes drills it towards long off and scampers for two more. Excellent running between the wickets.

Direct hit and it would've been interesting. A length ball around off, Root pushes it towards gully and calls for a run. The fielder there fires the throw at the striker's end but misses. Stokes is happy to have the strike.
Two more as this length ball outside off is smashed to the right side of the long off fielder.
Swing and a miss! Good length ball outside off, Stokes makes room outside off and tries to hammer it down town but fails to connect.
Another short of a length ball around middle, Root works it towards deep square leg for a run.
Short ball around off and middle, Root pulls it towards mid-wicket.
Back of a length ball around off, pulled for a single. England's lead now reads 250.
Low full toss around off and middle, Stokes powers it to deep mid-wicket. Roach does well to stop the ball with his boot. Two taken and it brings 50-run stand between the two.
Another short ball, this time Stokes charges down and pulls it down to deep mid-wicket for a single.
Landed around off, Root tucks it towards mid on and takes a run.
Good length ball around off, Stokes mistimes it towards mid-wicket for a single.
WIDE! Another short ball, this one is outside off. Stokes lets it go. Wided by the umpire.
Good bumper! Sharp from Roach as he realizes that fuller ball has been dispatched. Roach bends his back and bowls a sharp bouncer. Stokes does well to evade.
FOUR! Hammered down the ground! This is some batting from Stokes. A full ball around off, Stokes gives it a charge and sends it over mid off for another boundary.
On the pads, Root plays it towards mid on and calls for a single.
Full and just outside off, Root drives it towards deep cover for a single.

Dropped! Oh dear! A simple chance has been put down. Gabriel is fuming! John Campbell is the man. A length ball just outside off, Stokes looks to clear the long off fence again but he ends up miscuing it this time. It goes towards deep cover where Campbell settles himself nicely, gets both the hands but fails to hold on. Single for Stokes.
Good length ball outside off, Root guides it down to third man for a single.
Short and wide outside off, Root looks to cut but fails to connect.
Down the leg side, Root tries to flick but misses.
Overthrow! A length delivery around off, Root  pushes it towards point and takes a single. The fielder there fires a throw at the keeper's end but misses and concedes an extra run.
Shannon Gabriel will bowl from the other end.
14 from the over! Superb start for England. Wide outside off, Stokes once again gives it charge and punches it wide of the long off fielder. Two taken before the fielder can get around.
SIX! Monstrous! England need a few more of these and Stokes can certainly do that. Full and just outside off, Stokes comes down the track and slams it over long off for a huge six.
FOUR! Stokes gets the chance of freeing his arms and he does so nicely! Slightly short and just outside off, Stokes is down the track to punch it through the cover region for a boundary.
A single for Root now as he works this length ball on the pads towards fine leg.
Good length ball just around off, Root plays it towards point.
Run straightaway! And Stokes clears his intentions on the first ball. A fuller ball outside off, he powers it to deep cover for a single.

We are almost ready to begin! The West Indian players have made their way out to the middle. The two England batters, Ben Stokes and Joe Root stride out to the middle. Kemar Roach will start with the ball for West Indies. Ben Stokes to face the first ball. Here we go...

After an enthralling day's play on Day 4 where first West Indies batters didn't give an inch in the first two session but Broad and Woakes inflicted a collapse in the final one to make things interesting on the final day of this 2nd Test. England are ahead by 219 runs at the moment. It is them who will be desperate to go for the win while West Indies would not mind settling for a draw. England needs some quick runs and then maybe 60-odd overs to bowl West Indies out. West Indies, on the other hand, would look to take a couple of more quick wickets and try not to give easy runs. Let's see how things pan out when the teams arrive out in the middle. Welcome to our coverage of the final day's play of this Test match.
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

So, England are ahead by 219 runs. After how many runs they will feel safe? Maybe another 100 runs? Or maybe they will think to play the first session on Day 5 and try to bowl West Indies out in the remaining two sessions. Lots of ifs and buts to answer but well, you will get all the answers when you join us for the 5th day's play on Monday, 20th July 2020 at 1100 Local (1000 GMT). Till then, it is goodbye from our end.

Earlier in the day, after some fine batting performances from Brathwaite, Brooks and Chase, it looked like West Indies will bat out the entire day but once England opted for the second new ball, Stuart Broad breathed fire and took quick wickets to make the game interesting. However, Chase with his half ton made sure West Indies went past the follow-on score and forced England to bat again.

England needed quick runs in these few overs and they intended to do the same when they sent Ben Stokes and Jos Buttler to open the innings. However, Buttler fell without scoring and Crawley too didn't add much to the score. Roach picked both the wickets for West Indies. England finish the 4th day with a lead of 219 runs.
An exciting day of Test cricket comes to a close but the final day promises to be an equally interesting one with the possibility of all the results.

A single to end Day 4. A length delivery on middle and leg, Stokes tucks it towards mid on and calls for two but the fielder charges in and Stokes has to settle for a single. With that, it is STUMPS ON DAY 4.
Swing and a miss! A fuller ball just outside off, Stokes looks to launch it over long off but doesn't connect.
Landed around off on a good length, Root guides it down to third man for a single.
Beauty from Shannon! Slightly short and outside off, Root comes forward and looks to drive but misses.
Excellent shot but just one! Fuller and around off, Stokes drives it through mid off powerfully but Joseph at long off cuts it off.
Short and wide outside off, Stokes cuts it to deep point for two more. Didn't time it well there.
Full and just outside off, Root goes for the drive but misses. The ball kept low and went to the keeper on the bounce.
A couple for Root but off the inside edge as he tries to punch this length ball just around off towards the off side. It goes to fine leg and they take two.
Good length ball just around off, Stokes pushes it through covers and calls for two straightaway. Root though denies the second.
Shortish around off, Root taps it towards point and calls for a run.
Outside off, left alone.
Good length ball outside off, Stokes comes down the track and slams it to deep cover for a single.
Outside off, Stokes throws his bat at it but it goes towards third man off the bottom edge. Root and Stokes look for two but have to do with one.
Good length ball on off, Root pulls it towards fine leg and gets to the other end.
Full around off, Stokes plays it towards long on and looks for two but gets only one.
Outside off, Stokes looks to cut but misses.
Length ball on middle and leg, Stokes  taps it towards third man and gets a couple.
Short ball on off this time, Root pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for one.
No Ball! Shorter but down the leg side, Root looks to pull but misses. It is called a No Ball though as Gabriel oversteps his line.
Length ball outside off, Root strokes it behind square on the off side and gets run. He will keep the strike.
Good ball. Length delivery pitching outside off and coming back in, Root looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Fuller on off, Joe pushes it to mid off.
On the pads, Stokes glances it to the leg side and gets a run.
On the pads, Root flicks it to the on side and gets off the mark with a single. The lead now stands at 200!
Skipper Joe Root walks out at number 4.

Now that England have lost 2 quick wickets, will they change their strategy? Or they will still try to get quick runs. 2 more wickets before the close and West Indies might think even they have a chance here. Interesting..

OUT! BOWLED! The middle stump goes cartwheeling. Roach gets his second wicket of the innings and England's aggressive approach is backfiring here. Good length ball on middle and off, Crawley looks to go down town but misses and the ball takes the middle stump with it. Great sight for any bowler but a fast bowler's delight.
Length ball outside off, Stokes looks to hit but misses.
On the pads, Crawley looks to flick but the ball goes off his thigh pad for a single.
In the air but safe. Full on middle and off, Stokes looks to go over long off but does not get the distance. It goes high in the air but falls short of long off who comes running in.
Short ball on middle, Crawley pulls it to deep mid-wicket for a single.

FOUR! It does not matter how and where they come as long as they keep on coming. Length delivery outside off, Crawley looks to play it on the off side but gets a thick outside edge which takes the ball wide and past of the man at gully for a boundary.
Back of a length ball on  off, Stokes pulls it but there is protection at deep square leg so just a single.
Fuller and around off, played back to the bowler.
Low full toss around off, Stokes skips down the track to launch it over long on but mistimes it just wide of the mid on fielder. Gets just a single.
Length delivery around off, Crawley pushes it towards point and takes a quick run.
Almost another drag on! A good length ball just around off, Crawley looks to drive but gets a thick inside edge onto his pads.
No run. Shortish and just outside off, Crawley punches it towards short cover.
Flicked off the pads for a couple of runs. Full and around middle and leg, Crawley flicks it through mid-wicket and before the mid on can get around, two taken.
Short and around off and middle, this time he pulls it down to deep square leg for a single. A very good first over from Gabriel too.
Another ripper! Just past the outside edge. Gabriel bowls this in the channel, just outside off. Crawley has to play at it. He does so but the slight away movement means he is beaten.
Brilliant ball from Gabriel. Bangs it short and makes it to come back in. Crawley tries to defend but the ball sneaks through and goes over the stumps.
Bouncer on middle and leg, Crawley sits under it.
Length ball around off and middle, Stokes punches it down to long on for a single.
Back of a length ball on middle, Crawley looks to pull but fails to time it well. It drops towards the leg side off the upper part of his bat. Stokes calls for a single.
Shannon Gabriel to bowl from the other end.
Outside off, left alone. Successful over for West Indies ends.
Zak Crawley walks in at no. 3.
A single on the first ball. Full and around off, pushed towards cover for a single.

OUT! DRAGGED ON! Buttler goes for a duck and the plan to open with him fails. Full and outside off, Buttler sees the chance of freeing his arms. He throws his bat but ends up dragging the ball on his stumps. Idea start for West Indies as Buttler could've score really quickly.
Another fuller one, this one is played back to the bowler. Roach tries to field but misses as the ball hits the stumps at the bowler's end.
Very full ball around off, Buttler does well to block it out.
Runs straight away! A good length ball around off, Stokes looks to drive but the ball takes the outer half of the bat and goes towards covers. A single taken.

Right then! West Indies land a punch in Southampton  and England return the favor here in Manchester. Who will win the bout?  Well, that will be decided when both the teams face off for the final game at the same venue. That game will be played on 24th July 2020. It will start at 1100 (1000 GMT). We will wait for your company for it. Till then, goodbye and take care!

BEN STOKES IS NAMED PLAYER OF THE MATCH for his brilliant performance. Ben starts by saying that he is fine on being asked about the niggle and tells that he did not want to take a risk. On his long bowling spell, Stokes says that he is ready to give everything for the team. Feels that once he bowled 5-6 overs, he felt that he should just keep bowling. Adds that in the first innings, they felt that there wasn't much movement off the surface. Adds that they used the short ball tactics well. On his batting performance in both the innings, tells that both the innings were played at a different scenarios. Feels that the bowlers should get a lot of credit for their performance in the final session of Day 4. On him batting over 300 balls to get to his ton, Stokes laughs and says that he never thought he will face that many balls.

England skipper, Joe Root says that it was a brilliant week's cricket and says they have made progress in their batting and hopes to see more of 400+ scores. Tells they were in a position to finish it up and did so brilliantly. On Sibley, Root says that they want him to go out there and set the platform and tells that he is getting better with each game he plays. On Stokes, he says he does not surprise him as he leads the way in many ways and he keeps getting better and better. Tells he is a great example for everyone. Adds that Broad led the attack brilliantly and they know that he has a lot of cricket left in him. On the decisions to be made before the next Test, he says it was always going to be a challenge as they had all their bowlers fit and tells it is going to be tricky.

West Indies skipper, Jason Holder, says that they are disappointed with their performance but credits England for their performance. Mentions Stokes' performance in the game made a lot of difference. Tells that there are a few points to ponder on for them in the next couple of days, like whether they should come forward or stay back to play or leave the balls. Feels that they batted quite well for a decent amount of time but credits the English bowlers for coming hard. Says that there's no regret regarding the decision at toss and feels that Sibley and Stokes should be given the credit the way they batted. Tells that they will look to see how all the guys pull up and decide about the team for the next game. Finishes by saying that they are here for win and they will give their all in the decider.
Stay with us for the presentation...

England bowlers were superb with the ball in this innings even though there was hardly any assistance for them. Broad got one in the first over and then they kept coming and coming and got wickets at regular intervals. Brooks and Blackwood resisted with respective half tons but once they were dismissed, things became tough for the visitors and England eventually bundled them out well before the allotted overs for Day 5. Apart from skipper Joe Root who bowled 10 deliveries, all the bowlers got wickets at crucial moments to help the hosts level the series.

West Indies batters did superbly in the first innings and were playing calmly with Brathwaite, Brooks and Chase getting to their half-centuries. However, once England took the second new ball, West Indies lost their way and somehow managed to avoid the follow-on with Chase helping them do that. Broad and Woakes finished with 3 apiece while Curran got 2 and Stokes and Bess took 1 wicket.

Earlier in the game, after winning the toss, Holder opted to bowl first. They started well with a couple of wickets early on but Sibley and Stokes combined for a marathon stand and took England towards a huge total. Both brought up their respective tons. They eventually declared on 469/9. Discussions were going around regarding the approach of Sibley and Stokes during that partnership knowing the fact that there were chances of rain on Day 3. For the Windies bowlers, it was a long toil that lasted for nearly 2 days with Chase taking a fifer. As per the forecast, the entire day's play on Day 3 was washed out.

What a terrific comeback from England to level the series! After the Day 3 washout and then the way West Indies batters batted in the first innings, it looked like there was just one result, i.e. a draw but Broad with a brilliant spell turned things around first and then earlier on in the morning session, Ben Stokes with his fluent knock gave the side a terrific opportunity to seal the game.

OUT! Caught! Ollie Pope takes a stunner at short leg to seal the game! Floated delivery on middle and leg, Roach flicks it to the left of short leg. Pope gets a hand to it and the ball lobs away from him. He dives and takes a beauty to seal the game. ENGLAND WIN BY 113 RUNS!
Drinks Break!
Flighted outside off, Gabriel looks to defend but misses.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
On the stumps, SG defends it.
Floated outside off, Gabriel looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.
Tossed up outside off, Gabriel looks to defend but misses.
Floated on off, Gabriel plays it to mid on.

... Day 5, Final Session ...

A very good session of Test cricket. It looked like West Indies would lose just one wicket but the hard work, effort and commitment of Stokes ensured that they break the 100-run stand right before Tea and head to the break with momentum on their side. It was a fascinating session of cricket as after getting rid of Roston Case early in the session, it looked like the hosts were cruising but Blackwood joined Brooks out in the middle and the pair put up a brilliant fight with both getting to their respective half centuries and adding a 100-run stand. It looked like the duo had done enough and would go to Tea unscathed but right at the stroke of Tea, Blackwood fell prey to Stokes' vicious bouncer and it is England who will feel like they have the momentum. West Indies are still in this with a fighting chance to draw. England, on the other hand, still have a lot to do as Brooks is out there and Dowrich and West Indies' best batter in the side, Holder still to come. So just over 42 overs to be bowled in the final session and 5 wickets in hand we are set for a thrilling finale. Do not miss out on this as it promises to be a great end to this Test. Join us for the final session at 1615 local (1515 GMT) to find out which way this Test goes.

On off, defended by Brooks.
Full and on off, driven firmly but straight to mid off.
FOUR! Third boundary in the over. Full and outside off again as Curran searches for some movement. Blackwood creams it through the covers and the ball races to the fence.
In the channel outside off, Blackwood lets it be..
FOUR! Just over mid off. Blackwood is not worried about the fielder and he will continue to play his shots. Full and outside off, he lofts it over mid off for a boundary.
Outside off, left alone.

FOUR! Lucky though! Short and outside off, bouncer a little too extra. Surprising because even Broad and Woakes have not got that much bounce. Blackwood tries to leave it alone but the ball gets him big and takes the top edge and races to the fence over the leaping slip fielder.
4 down already. West Indies in a spot of bother. Would they be looking for some assistance from the skies? Who knows? Will they get? Only time will tell.
Full on off, Brooks plays it to mid on.
Effort ball from Broad. Brooks hops and dabs it onto the ground.
Very full on off, Brooks blocks it towards mid off.
Length ball on off, Brooks keeps it out.
Blackwood opens his account. Broad bowls it on middle and leg, Blackwood turns it to the leg side and takes a run to get off the mark.
Good length ball on off, Blackwood defends it with a straight bat.
Third leave in a row as  Curran continues bowling way outside off.
One more leave as Curran once again bowls this length ball outside off.
A leave as this one is outside off.
Full again and around off, Brooks once again times it well but finds mid off.
FOUR! Creamed through covers! Full and outside off, Brooks leans into the shot and smashes it through the covers. Two fielders give it a chase but the ball wins the race.
Good length ball around off and middle, Brooks blocks it out.
Jermaine Blackwood joins Shamrah Brooks out in the middle. Change is bowling too as Sam Curran comes to bowl.

OUT! LBW! No shot offered and Chase has to go. He will not review this. Broad has his third and West Indies in a massive, massive trouble. A length ball outside off, Chase thinks it will not come back in much and shoulders arms. However, to his surprise, the ball comes back in nicely and hits him on the pads. A loud appeal follows and the umpire raises his finger. Chase keeps walking and the replays show why. It would've been waste of a review had he taken that.
FOUR! First boundary for Chase. A fuller length ball on middle and leg, Chase whips it to deep mid-wicket and the ball races to the fence.
Shortish and around off, Brooks stays on the back foot and taps it towards the off side and takes a quick single.
On the pads this time, Chase tucks it towards fine leg for a run.
This time Woakes bowl it closer to the off stump and Chase pokes at it to get beaten. Lucky not to edge on that one.
In the channel outside off, shaping further away. An easy leave for Chase.
Brooks lets this length ball outside off go to the keeper by covering his stumps.
Full and on the pads, this time he flicks it towards deep square leg for a single to open his account.
Fuller and around off, pushed towards covers.
Nice bowling. Slightly shortish and just outside off. Shapes away after pitching nicely as Chase tries to play but withdraws his bat away at the last moment.
Another leave as Woakes once again is slightly wide outside off on a good length.
In the channel outside off, left alone.
A back of a length ball but the line is not right for this one as it is down the leg side. Brooks has no problems leaving it alone.
Outside off, left alone.
Another fuller one, pushed back to the bowler who gets down to field but makes a half stop as the ball goes towards mid on. No runs taken.
Fuller again, this time Brooks pushes it back to Broad.

Poor shot from Brooks but Broad lured him doing this.He this time invites the batsman for the drive by bowling it full. Brooks obliges but the ball moves away to beat the outside edge. He could've easily left that alone.
Fuller but outside off, Brooks lets it go to the keeper.
Stuart Broad to bowl from the other end. 6-2-12-2 from him so far.
Good length ball around off, it is worked towards point for a run.
FOUR! Full and outside off, Brooks drives it nicely through point and the ball races away to the fence.
Slightly shorter in length, Brooks keeps it out off his back foot.
Another good length ball around off, Brooks pushes it towards point.
Good length ball around off, blocked by Brooks.
A good length ball outside off to begin the session. Brooks shoulders arms.

Time for the second and most important session of the Test match. A couple of wickets quickly and we might see an early finish. The English players have made their way out to the middle. Roston Chase and Shamarh Brooks stride out too. A task in hand for both the batters. 74 overs left in the day, weather permitting. Chris Woakes with the ball. Here we go...
... Day 5, Session 2 ...

West Indies have a lot to think about as everything that could possibly go wrong has went wrong in the first session of the final day. They leaked runs to begin the day. Needing 312 to win but more importantly surviving 85 overs, the tourists would have wanted their openers to at least see off the session but Campbell's poor day continued as after dropping a sitter of Stokes earlier in the day, he was dismissed in the very first over. The tourists have looked lackluster with the willow and are in a troublesome position. They would look to improve and have a much better second session. Can the tourists put on a fight or will England have a fruitful second session as well? Join us at 1340 Local (1240 GMT) to find out.

A brilliant morning session for England first hour or less with the bat and the remaining with the ball. The day started off with some aggressive batting by Stokes sprinkled with some luck as he was dropped by John Campbell. An aggressive innings from Stokes gave the hosts a lead in excess of 300 and after declaring with the lead of 311, the hosts would have looked for a couple of wickets from their new ball bowlers. That is what they got, the returning Broad proved why he shouldn't be dropped as he picked two and his new ball partner Woakes getting one. The hosts are clearly on top of this game.

Another on-field decision referred upstairs as England think they have another wicket. Chase is the man in question. Let's see what the replays have to show. No problems with the front foot. However,the Ball Tracker shows that it would miss the leg stump.

NOT OUT! Missing the leg stump by some distance. A waste of a review from them. Good length ball on middle, comes back in once again. Chase tries to flick but misses and is hit on the pads. A loud appeal from Broad and others but not out says the umpire. Root has a word with his bowler and opts for the review. Time for the replays. Front foot is fine. Is it hitting the stumps? Ball Tracker says no, missing the leg pole. So, Chase stays to return for the second session as it is LUNCH ON DAY 5!
Good leave, very good leave. A length delivery just around off, Chase covers his stumps and lets it go.

Huge appeal but that was clearly going down. It was angled in from outside off, Chase tried to work it on the leg side but missed to get hit on the pads. An appeal from England but nothing from the umpire.
Another leave as this one too is well outside off.
Outside off on a good length, Chase leaves it alone.
Good length ball on middle, Brooks works it towards deep square leg for a run.
Landed on a good length on middle, Chase works it on the leg side.
Very full around off, pushed towards point.
Superb delivery from Woakes. A slightly shortish ball just around off, Chase pokes at it but gets beaten.
On the pads, Brooks flicks it towards fine leg for a single to get off the mark.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Shortish ball outside off, Brooks lets it go to the keeper.
A bouncer around off, Chase ducks under it.
Roston Chase is in now.

OUT! Knocked him over with a beauty! Another one bites the dust and England are on fire. Brilliant from Broad. A brilliant ball again. Pitches just outside off and nips back in sharply to beat the inside edge and topple the timbers behind. West Indies in all sorts of trouble early on.
Good length ball around off blocked.
FOUR! Slammed through the covers. Full and outside off, he frees his arms and creams it through the cover region and the ball races away to the fence.
Outside off, a leave from Hope.
A length ball just around off, Hope keeps it out off his front foot.
Shamarh Brooks is the next man in. Three slips and a gully waiting.

OUT! LBW! That is plumb and Brathwaite is not taking the DRS. He just walks as he knows where he was standing. A good length ball that comes back in from just around off, Brathwaite looks to defend but misses to get hit on the back pad. Huge appeal follows and the umpire agrees. Brathwaite has a word with Hope but keeps walking. The replays later show that it would've been umpire's call on hitting the wickets.
On the pads, Hope nudges it to fine leg for a single.
Full and just around off, Hope looks to cream it through covers but fails to time it well. It went uppishly towards the cover fielder.
A solid front foot block by Hope this time to this good length ball around off.
Shortish and on the body, Brathwaite hops and works it down to fine leg for a single.
Length ball down the leg side. Brathwaite lets it be.
Landed around off on a good length, blocked by Hope off his back foot.
In the channel outside off, this time Hope covers his stumps and lets it be.
Another one that comes back in from around off, this time Hope does well to block it away.

Appeal from behind the wickets but Broad suggests it is high. A length ball around off, comes back in sharply. Hope looks to block but misses to get hit on the pad. The keeper and the slip cordon appeal but Broad does not and tells it's too high. The replays later roll in and confirm the same.
Full ball around off and middle, Hope keeps it out.
Good length ball just outside off, Hope looks to defend but misses.
Length ball on off, Brathwaite once again blocks it to get through the over.
Good seam movement as he bowls it on a length and makes it to shape away. Brathwaite defends it towards point.
Length ball on off, KB pushes it to mid off.
Down the leg side, Brathwaite looks to flick but misses.
On the pads, Hope flicks it towards fine leg and gets to the other end.
Good length ball on middle and off, Hope defends it with a dead bat.
Broad over corrects and misses his line as he delivers this way down the leg side.

Oh! This one keeps low but unfortunately it misses the stump by just a bit. Good length ball outside off, it shapes in a bit but does not come back enough to take the edge of Brathwaite's defensive willow or stump.
Good length ball on the fourth stump line, Brathwaite is aware of his off pole and leaves it alone.
Outside off, KB leaves it alone.
On off, Brathwaite blocks.
On the pads, Brathwaite looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pad.
Inswinging full ball on off, Hope keeps his eyes on the ball and blocks it right under his eyes.
Length ball on off, Hope pushes it to point.
Beauty! Good length ball pitching outside off and coming back in. Hope looks to play it straight but misses. Shai is lucky as the ball was just whiskers away from the edge.
On the pads, Hope looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.
Back of a length ball on off, Shai defends it.
Length ball on off, Hope defends it off the front foot.
Bouncer! Brathwaite watches it closely and sits under it.
On the pads, Brathwaite flicks it to the on side.
FOUR! Lovely shot! Broad overcooks this delivery and bowls it too full around off, Brathwaite gets on his front foot and drives it wonderfully through mid off for a boundary.
On the pads, Hope flicks it stylishly towards fine leg and gets a single.
Length ball way outside off, Hope leaves it alone.
Good length ball on off, Hope defends it with a dead bat.
Very full ball on middle, Brathwaite blocks it out nicely.
On middle and leg, this one is played towards mid-wicket.
Good length ball outside off, left alone.
Shortish and around off and middle, Brathwaite keeps it out.
Around off, solidly defended.

FOUR! Fine shot from Brathwaite. Good length ball outside the off stump, Brathwaite punches it through the covers. The fielder chases it, makes a diving stop. The umpires check if it is a clean stop. It is not is what the replays confirm so a boundary for Brathwaite.
Chris Woakes to partner Stuart Broad with the new ball.
Outside off, Hope lets it be. Successful first over for England.
Shai Hope is the next man in.

OUT! Caught Behind! A last second review but it is a successful one. A full ball outside off, Campbell once again looks to drive it through the covers but fails to connect. There is a loud appeal but nothing from Buttler from behind the wickets. Root thinks and thinks and calls for the review at the last moment. And, the replays show that there is a clear spike. So, England have drawn first blood in the very first over.
Review time! England think they have a wicket caught behind. A very late review from them. Is there a nick? Oh, yes, there is!
FOUR! Campbell is off the mark in a fine fashion. Full and outside off, Campbell leans into the shot and drives it through point for a boundary.
Good length ball outside off, left alone.
Good length ball around off, pushed toward point.
Runs for West Indies straightaway! Three of them. A fuller ball on the pads, Brathwaite flicks it down to deep square leg for three.
